@SteveL-MSFT Any thoughts on the readability and ease of coding for what I proposed? 

> definitions with attributers becomes a mystery

@iSazonov Can you expand on that? I'm not sure I understand.

> In fact, we must define a graph.

Could you psuedo code an example of what that would look like?

@iSazonov what would a JSON solution look like?

Maybe this?

```json
{
  "AllParameterSets": {
    "MandatoryParameters": [],
    "OptionalParameter": [
      "C",
      "D",
      "E",
      "F"
    ],
    "ParameterMutexGroups": {
      "CD": [
        "C",
        "D"
      ],
      "EF": [
        "E",
        "F"
      ]
    }
  },
  "ParameterSetA": {
    "MandatoryParameters": [
      "A"
    ],
    "OptionalParameters": [
      "A1",
      "A2"
    ],
    "ParameterMutexGroups": {}
  },
  "ParameterSetB": {
    "MandatoryParameters": [
      "B"
    ],
    "OptionalParameters": [
      "B1",
      "B2"
    ],
    "ParameterMutexGroups": {}
  }
}
```

```powershell
[ordered]@{
    AllParameterSets = [ordered]@{
        MandatoryParameters = @()
        OptionalParameter = @('C','D','E','F')
        ParameterMutexGroups = [ordered]@{
            CD = @('C', 'D')
            EF = @('E', 'F')
        }
    }
    ParameterSetA = [ordered]@{
        MandatoryParameters = @('A')
        OptionalParameters = @('A1', 'A2')
        ParameterMutexGroups = @{}
    }
    ParameterSetB = [ordered]@{
        MandatoryParameters = @('B')
        OptionalParameters = @( 'B1', 'B2')
        ParameterMutexGroups= @{}
    }
} | ConvertTo-Json -Depth 4
```
